A first virtual operator will win Czechia this year.
Maybe
The market in Czechia is relatively advanced, our operators offering almost the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, who would force conventional operators to lower prices.
Maybe he won't be missing for a long time.
We have repeatedly mentioned on Mobil.cz the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTú (The Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in us than in the rest of the Union, confirmed it.
Thus, following the latest steps of the European Commission in the area of roaming fee regulation, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators less expensive than in the country.
How is it possible that Czech prices remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that goes far beyond 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTú), who declared several times that there was no place in Chechnya for another operator, is chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network seems to be no longer very lucky (in fact, now, it would find only difficult to find frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has resulted in a considerable decrease in prices, to which conventional operators should, in turn, also react.
Yet, even before the entry of the holidays such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market, voices similar to what we hear today at home would be heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We are not obliged to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and become the country's fifth operator.
We add that behind the Mobilking, there is the Penta financial group, which has among other things the U:fon in Czechia.
The advantage of virtual operators being the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they need much less customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from relatively high construction, operation and maintenance costs of the mobile network.
Thus, in the world, virtual operators appear as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers, in Britain, text messages at least twice as expensive as its competitors.
But, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, placing on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity.
This operator is specifically aimed at men.
"The real men choose Mobilking - an operator that they like and to whom they can trust," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, exploiting this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work with us too.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone's spokesperson, in doubt: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
All the more so that he is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services."
In Czechia, no chance, the mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in Czechoslovakia, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this project successfully, but negotiations in Czechia are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our area," said in a telephone entertainment for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesman of the financial group Penta.
It therefore indirectly confirmed that the operators in Czechia were not, in any case, in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible so that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of business customers, has not, for quite a long time, hidden its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We are very much able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already held negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have been able to move forward in the negotiations," says Pavel Kaidl's spokesman.
The future is perhaps promising.
According to non-official information, it seems that we could perhaps accommodate the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by a total silence.
"At the moment, we do not think there is any place on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is compared to other very specific ones.
At the moment, no subject has been contacted by a complex and serious project in this area," said Vladimir Sršeň of the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also relate to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokesperson Martina Kemrová states in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not registered for the moment a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: "It is practically excluded that a virtual operator appears in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited period of time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone instead directs its attention to the completion of requests to obtain its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický said in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we believe means most customer input.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to establish a common network for a fast mobile internet."
The responsible authorities: in phase with the operators
The mobile operators' approach is easily understandable, another operator's entry would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and thus to a decrease in profit.
What, then, is it good to facilitate the arrival of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to hear themselves as larks in the fair. Chicane accompanying the creation of the U:phone also testifies to it.
The greatest apparent pressure on the ČTú, when creating the U:fon, was the one exercised by the T-Mobile company.
This is evidenced by information available to the public from the ČTú web pages.
Today, the U:fon is ready to use as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted on this subject: "Competition on the mobile market has also recently been enhanced by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and above all its services, to high requirements."
But given the attitude of mobile operators here, the indifference of Czech regulators seems disconcerting.
However, this is not just the attitude of the ČTú, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in Czechia.
The latter belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
However, the latter adopts, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the relevant virtual operator regarding the rental of the required infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached for the time being, because the offer of potential stakeholders has not previously presented sufficient interest to conventional operators," said Kristián Chalupa of the UOHS Department of External Relations in response to our question.
A statement thus made would not surprise the representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, care, so that no one takes advantage of his position on the market, such a statement is more than misleading.
Even more so, Kristián Chalupa adds: "Out abroad, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their market entry has contributed to a decrease in the prices of mobile telephone services."
However, pressure in the sense of honest market functioning and lower prices does not appear to be part of the UOHS interests.
What is really shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if it really is a coincidence, naturally arises.
In the same way, a strictly identical price of petrol at all service stations is likely to be due to the chance and the hard fight of competition.
"The Office has not noted, in this regard, signs of anti-competitive behaviour, therefore, there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore none of them has an increased responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even the telecommunication regulator," said Chaloupa.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTú that telecommunications are, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
However, some legal experts propose another view of things: in order for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained each time.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on his network.
This is how he necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the UOHS that three mobile operators are visibly proceeding in a similar manner.
However, complaints from many interested parties (including GTS Novera, mentioned above) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Taking responsibility for the ČTú is a fairly common turn in communications, through which the UOHS washes its hands of the case.
We have already encountered this kind of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to introduce the recently adopted Telecommunications Act, an extension of ČTú's powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised to improve the situation.
However, the representatives of the UOHS must know very well, but their interests seem to be elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work.
However, the operation of a sort of virtual pseudooperators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unclear.
These are companies publishing their own price lists of mobile telephone services, but they are only partially public.
In most cases, there are firms dealing with multi-level marketing.
Specific mobile telephone services are provided for example by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms generally reach only elected persons.
The magic tour consists of the fact that the company in front of the operator figure of a classic business client, which commands a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important client, she gets special price offers (and others).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
"If there were to happen what you are referring to, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would consider and which could lead to an end to collaboration with the company in question," replied our question regarding this problem Martina Kemrová.
However, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity has not been reached up to those responsible for mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator shall take a decision against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them non-neglectable benefits, and at the same time, as opposed to actual virtual operators, they do not threaten them at all with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický indicates the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are only used by a percentage of negligible customers.
In addition, they are obliged to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot have it fully, in the way ordinary customers of mobile operators do."
That is precisely what should seem strange to ČTú.
In addition, another question arises in UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the UOHS has relatively broad powers to reveal such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the operators' explanations, which state that there is no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions would prohibit it.
When we will no longer be the most expensive country
As we have mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has resulted in a considerable decrease in service prices.
However, virtually in all the countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators were trying, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
It is precisely at this level that regulatory bodies in developed countries, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Both through formal measures and through informal pressure, they ended up obtaining the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are dealing with this issue in the way a hot potato is being disposed of by transmitting it to a near target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than profitable in these cases.
But don't throw the sleeve after the cockroach.
If the flow information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear in our home, the Czech mobile market may be moving back.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the UOHS will be unable to remain impatible in the face of the rejection (to discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the Best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the day of Czech nationality, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the Kde national anthem housev m aj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem has again been registered by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with heart and an instrumental version.
The song is provided by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiaš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the anthem's arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
As previously entrusted to the Český rozhlas (Czech Public Radio), he chose for the interpretation of solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I was trying to take care that the two singers, as well as the choir, had a good dictionary, so that one could understand the words, which they sang simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate, next year, its 175th anniversary.
The song Kde housev m'j rang for the first time in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des savetiers), the Czech original play by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by music by František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously took it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couple naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It will remain one of seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
