The Sudets called for a referendum in the USA
In 1945, the Germans of the South asked that Šumava be integrated into the United States.
This stems from a letter filed in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (Scientific Library of the Bohème du Sud).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Germans from the South addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
This is also the result of a preserved letter in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans of Český Krumlov in the letter urged the American President not to allow "šumavská župa" (region of forests south of Bohème) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation well, and we want to be sure that the words proclaim that American troops come into German territory not in oppression and enemies, but in liberators," is written in the letter, "People, to whom Šumava's fate holds its heart."
Given that the rallying in Czechoslovakia is allegedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - that of brutality, senseless attitude, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter urge the American President to take into his hands the protectorate of Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe, that you would grant this territory to a foreign State to us, that oppresses and destroys minorities and that has not contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of the quarter of millions of inhabitants," is the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of "Czech Oppressors".
If the President of the USA doubted the Germans' opinion of Šumava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether his inhabitants wanted to be part of the USA, or to live under the US patronage.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given the current knowledge of the history of the post-war, appear somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it well illustrates the expectations of the Germans of the Sudetean period.
While the Czech Germans had to at least find out that the question of their expulsion from the Republic would arise, very few of them had such a possibility.
Some were waiting for the United States and Great Britain to obtain a certain type of autonomy for the Southeast.
Others thought they would just stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as German of České Budějovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war, he was captured by the English and placed in the Holstein capture camp, dozens of Czech Germans came to see him to teach them Czech.
"They thought that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them," Chalupa said.
None of the Germans captured in Czechoslovakia before the war thought that he would be expelled from the Republic following the Beneš Decrees.
