Rats also have feelings
A rat or a cockroach fled in the face of danger, does that mean he also feels fear?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles of the answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else has so far been able to prove it just as we cannot prove that other human beings have a conscience.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains present the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or in general consciousness, we enter difficult terrain because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, he does the same thing as many other animals: he does death, escape or attack.
Human beings behave in the same way, that is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make the transposition of our subjective life to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that circuits associated almost always with human consciousness include prefrontal lateral cortex (because of its involvement in short-term memory and leadership and enforcement functions).
This vast region is much more developed in human beings than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
All the less so for these aspects of our conscience that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that human beings differ even from other primates.
Another significant characteristic could reside in the linguistic nature of the Man: a large part of his existence being related to language, this often means that his conscience depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if the conscience was not to depend on the language, it would certainly influence it, so that the animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ a lot from most of our states of conscience.
That is why it is also difficult to determine what the consciousness can look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, does not allow itself to be measured or, because of this particular Hardware, to analyze on the basis of our own experience, then its observation poses major problems.
Most of my developments refer to the content of the conscious experience, but there is another aspect of the consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
Animal awareness processes could be examined without regard to their content, and that is exactly what happened in short-term memory studies of primates, particularly with the example of visualization.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on the nervous correlations of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both can be identical or not.
