"I photograph the master out of the scene to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no scissors.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, released from all tensions to obtain the relaxed appearance of man or woman.
On one side the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in these unknown moments of the general public, where one discovers intimate gestures and stolen views of artists who do not care to get on stage.
The German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatre of some performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known side of the artists.
In this project, the photographer resumes the specific iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of Flamenco Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" may be no one but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists capable of conveying on stage passion, sadness, joy... by captivating the public.
To capture moments of personality from these artists, you don't have to take pictures on stage.
They have a clean personality and character.
I was interested in creating an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera the moments of personality of the flamenco stars."
With the festival "Chant Popular des Mines", Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to photograph the singers, guitarists or dancers with a plated camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of the camera and the material, recall the classic photography.
The implementation of various stylistic means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not about dance or singing in itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captivates the public with his art.
The search for the essentials and magic has been the constant of this work that has been presented these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
Flamenco stars like Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy photographed artists.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a collection book of portraits exhibited at the gallery.
The passion for Bauer's portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of old sports" ("SportART Project").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves photographing the portrait of people, knowing them and being able to enter their lives for a longer or longer moment.
I think in the photograph the portrait is the most difficult kind.
You're standing in front of people, characters you sometimes don't know or leave you just a few minutes to be able to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true."
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people", is exhibited at the Galerie El Fotómata, located at the 20th Street of the Mata, parallel to the Peupleraie d'Hercule, which will be open until October 16.
