Interview - Blood returned safe
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of his foundation, and his president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice because Hema-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And above all, he regained the confidence of the public who had been seriously shaken by the scandal of blood contaminated in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and public grunt, in February 1994, the Government of Canada instituted a public investigation, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would not happen again.
While Judge Krever was late in filing his report, some provinces had set up a committee to plan for a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee has completed this mandate.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, barely 38 per cent of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalled.
The situation was discouraging.
In an effort to improve the safety of blood products and on-the-spot work during the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said proudly before affirming that in early 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile."
Hema-Québec applied the precautionary principle from its inception on 28 September 1998.
At that time, many cases of the human form of the disease of the mad cow, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, were emerging in Europe.
"And we didn't know at all whether this disease could be transmitted by blood.
It was then based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, that when it is not known and a serious disease may arise, in the case of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom was refused since 1980.
A few years ago, however, there was no doubt that this disease was transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle applied had meaning."
In 1999 a much more sensitive technique for HIV testing appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (TAN) that allow the presence of the virus itself and not the anti-virus virus to be directly detected in the blood of donors, based on the tests used to date.
The NTAs have allowed to shorten the silent period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
This has substantially reduced the risk that some donors are infected without knowledge and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV through a blood product occurs.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health," says the head of the management of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the security of our products.
We never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year on Réunion Island, the Chikungunya virus, which, like the West Nile virus, was transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary continued before stressing that, in addition to a security supply, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient supplies.
"The needs are increasing because the population is growing.
As anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need red blood cell or platelet recharge.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the blood donor network, which averages only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
Every person in health, aged 18 and older who meets the eligibility criteria, however, can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who propose their blood are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is severed, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this network of donors as they age and can no longer give their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Today's life is so scary, we rarely find the time to spend an hour giving of his blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec provides not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye cells and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Québec which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste adds to a blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth cord blood sample and we plan to take more than a thousand a year.
It should begin to be proposed for grafts at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood sampling program as very popular.
"Mothers are disappointed they can't have access to it," because Hema-Québec has no means to propose this complex and costly program in all hospitals in Quebec.
