Over-the-counter psychology: why do we spend more money?
In auction sales, buyers tend to spend more and overestimate the goods.
Neurology and Economics researchers from the University of New York have succeeded in updating the neurological and economic bases of this apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as auction sales on eBay, and that is why they prefer to even pay too high a price.
These researches have attempted to develop a neurological scheme of this type of "game" using experimental auction sales.
One of the volunteer groups played the loto, while the other group took part in a playful auction sale, while using a functional magnetic resonance imaging process (RMF), researchers analyzed the active brain areas of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the sale of auctions whose essential element is the auction of one third, the whole under the brain trunk, called stritatum, was moving intensively during the loss of the part.
This part of the brain, alongside several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the leak in the face of the violent reaction of the stratum.
In support of their theories, economic members of this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
In these cases, three groups were overcrowded against a partner, under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they did so.
In another group, they promised that if, in addition, they would get out of the game, then they would receive an additional $15 in reward.
While the third group received the $15 before the auctions, the members of the group also lost that money, in case they lost the auctions.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was placed on one victory, while at the other, on failure.
By thus proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the player team "against failure" were willing to take higher steps than those performed by the control group and the "to win".
