Hepatitis: when should we consult a doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
Hepatitis virus patients in Hungary are estimated to be 100 miles away, but only seven miles after treatment, which is because patients often do not know they are carriers of the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to liver-related infections caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and yellowness are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases generated differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogens, are propagated primarily in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g.: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and organic liquids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, vaccination against A and B viruses is also recommended. There is no vaccine against C.
Hepatitis A symptoms appear two to three weeks after the consumption of contaminated foods, in general, accompanied by a poor general condition, weakness, stomach and nausea.
Then it develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible yellowish, the saddles become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. The healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year, one million people die of the most serious form of this disease, such as liver cancer or cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients are not aware of the virus, because the pathogen destroys the cells of the liver in a sly way. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular testing.
Pollution is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattooed.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic type C hepatitis worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor who treats you as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of infection disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
On 30 September is the World Day of Hepatitis, organized for the first time in 2004 by the organizations representing the sick in all parts of the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
