The smart car imitates the bourdon's flight
What would be the best way to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if it is not the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
Like, for example, that of bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, which took place in Japan, the budding bees gave the strategic starting idea to Nissan engineers, to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with Tokyo University, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-robotized, BR23C-type system, which he has equipped with bee qualities, with the ultimate objective being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
In the course of its flights, each bee is its own space, of oval shape, which actually resembles much of our safe protection shell - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and technological public relations of the brand.
The bee's face-eye plays an important role, since it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the face-eye, engineers approached the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles at 180 degrees angle and at a distance of 2 metres in front of BR23C, evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the microprocessor, which transforms it into avoidance maneuver immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Contrary to any existing system, this avoidance maneuver is carried out in an instinctive manner.
"If it wasn't, the mini auto robot couldn't react fast enough to avoid the obstacle," says Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must be carried out in a blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be of two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees possess to avoid other bees, in our case, only the rotating movement, acceleration and slowing down as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini auto robot could be used.
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and whose energy concentration is greater, making their life longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not data processing, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism should only deal with a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilo-bytes of continuous memory.
There is no need for memory of a capacity of giga-bytes, or even mega-bytes.
This is the first step towards the design of an instant avoidance technology. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will make its entry into the cars manufactured in series in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
