Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - the Central Bureau of Statistics of Hungary communicates.
Industrial export prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to the previous year, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of domestic and export price fluctuations, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared with those of the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to those of the previous year.
Domestic industrial selling prices rose to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent, compared to the previous month.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry have only increased by 0.1% compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (1.8 percent), with first, the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 percent, then, the production of shoes with 2.5 percent monthly increase.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical and chemical manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
This has resulted in a deflation in the oil processing sectors (1.4 per cent), the manufacture of machinery and electrical equipment (0.9 per cent), as well as a minimal increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry increased from 0.2% to 0.9%.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, representing a significant weight in domestic industrial exploitation, prices increased by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices established by the authorities since 1 July.
In a twelve-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sale of processing sectors, the oil processing sector prices have been the most significant increase (32.4%).
In the metallurgy manufacturing sector, prices rose by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food production, beverages and tobacco, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price reductions have occurred in the textile and textile sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of machinery and electrical equipment (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, the price increase increased by 0.6 percent to 9.1 percent.
Throughout the processing industry, prices increased by 10.2% in the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 per cent in the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and by the allocation of sectors, in August, it was the investment profit-making sectors that showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and material-producing sectors for subsequent processing did not experience any change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and material production sectors for further processing (16.8%).
In the consumer goods production sectors, 6.8 per cent inflation was measured, while in the profit-making sectors a 1.4 per cent decrease was achieved.
Industrial export prices in HUF increased 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent in 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment decreased by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro, and by 7.1 per cent compared to the dollar. Compared to the month of August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent against the euro and 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
