Mp3 reader pointed to the finger, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for a prolonged period using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent injuries to the hearing.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a press release in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the unexpected and recently identified health risks (Cssseri) of the EU, published today.
"of this scientific report- let's read in the note- it turns out that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full-volume music using portable musical devices, for more than one hour per day and per week, are at risk of permanent loss of hearing ability."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable musical devices and mobile phones at full volume can unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable manner," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to scientific data, the EU is responsible for a clear risk and we must react quickly.
The most important thing is to raise awareness of consumers and make this information public.
We also need to review existing systems of control in view of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can follow new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise generated by them.
"Scientists-conclude the EU Executive - confirm that there are good reasons to be concerned, and that the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and other interested parties what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100DB, but the concern increases as to hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to limit these data using solutions such as reduction of levels and duration of exposure to noise.
The Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical devices, who listen to full-volume music (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the current limits on the maximum level of noise at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for prolonged periods are at risk of permanent loss of hearing ability after 5 years.
This is of interest to 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified to about 2.5 million and 10 million people in the U.S.
