The supercolle to walk on the walls.
Win the laws of gravity thanks to a super glue and, in the future, walk on the walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centres, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring just 2.5 cm square, the researchers managed to hold a 100 kilogram body on a vertical wall.
ETUDE- The U.S. journal Science has published the findings of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know who use a specific structure of carbon, called nano carbon tubes.
"The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a spaghetti pile." Explain Zhong Lin Wang from the Georgia Institute of Technology of Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by the legs of the geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that make it possible to ensure the animal, a perfect adherent.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Téflon, and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, that he "is easily detached from the wall" explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
MARKET ON THE MURS? –"This material could be used as a temporary adhesive" adds Liming Dai.
Could it be to walk on walls like Spiderman? Perhaps it is, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use such as connection between electronic devices, since carbon nano tubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications may concern aerospace engineering.
For now, no superheroes.
THE OTHER RESEARCH- The University of Berkeley, California, is also looking for a new adhesive.
In an article of the American Chemical Society magazine, Californian researchers presented an adhesive made of microfibers such as hair, which self-cleans dust during the movement on a surface to ensure perfect and constant adherence.
